\begin_layout Standard
The Perreault–Leigh and van Oest models are easy to construct tests for.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 be the standard empirical estimator of the probability matrix (i.e., the
 agreement matrix divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the number of items).
 Then let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 be an estimator of the model-implied probability matrix.
 We can estimate this in an ad-hoc manner, see the appendix for details.
 Our test statistic is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T=n\sum_{i=1}^{C}\sum_{j=1}^{C}\frac{\left(\hat{F}_{ij}-\hat{G}_{ij}\right)^{2}}{\hat{G}_{ij}},\label{eq:chisq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-distributed with 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}-2C-1=(C-1)^{2}$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
\end_layout

